@node intro "Introduction.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Intro
  ~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   This is a MACC - Mouse ACCelerator with a little more settings than
   most other maccs I've seen. Try it out!

   It is a commodity with a GUI that will automatically open on startup
   if there is no prefs file.

   I wrote it because I wasn't happy with the available mouse speed
   settings in OS4. (I have high demands :-))


@endnode

@node install "Installation.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Installation
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   Copy the program anywhere. WBStartup is a good place. It needs no
   special installation.

   When you have started Macc the first time you need to save prefs to
   prevent the window from opening every time you start it.


@endnode

@node req "Requirements.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   This program requires Amiga OS4 (update4 for wheel acceleration).


@endnode

@node usage "Usage.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Usage
  ~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   As a mouse accelerator it has quite a few settings. Most notable
   is the ability to set different accelerations when you have different
   mousebuttons pressed.

   First some background info about what movement thresholds are:
   As some might have figured out, the mouse pointer isn't really moving
   over the screen, rather it is positioned on different places on the
   screen with short intervals. Often every vertical blank of the screen,
   i.e. normally between 50-85 times a second, input device "reads" or
   get sent new mouse movement data from the PS/2 or USB port where the
   mouse is.

   What this all means is that if you move the mouse at a certain speed
   the mouse pointer must jump a certain number of pixels on the screen
   to reflect the movement. It is the length of the "jumps" that we interpret
   as mouse speed.

   A threshold is therefore a certain "speed" after which we want to
   apply some amount of acceleration by multiplying the "jump" or "speed"
   by some value to make it proportionally larger or smaller.


   @{u}Mouse Movements@{uu}

      @{b}First threshold@{ub}
        Apply acceleration when the mouse moves faster than this value.
        This applies when you move the mouse without any mousebuttons pressed
        down. Settingt his, or any threshold, to 1 means that the acceleration
        will always be used, hence you get a linear mouse movement as we using
        Amiga are used to, but a bit faster or slower.
   
      @{b}Second threshold@{ub}
        Apply a second acceleration when the mouse moves faster than this
        value. This value must be larger than the first threshold.
   
      @{b}Left threshold@{ub}
        Apply acceleration after this threshold when the left mousebutton
        is pressed.
   
      @{b}Middle threshold@{ub}
        Apply acceleration after this threshold when the middle mousebutton
        is pressed.
   
      @{b}Right threshold@{ub}
        Apply acceleration after this threshold when the right mousebutton
        is pressed.

      You need to experiment with all these values to get it as you like.
      Changing the values in the GUI will instantly change the mouse behavior
      making it easy to test.


   @{u}Mouse Wheel@{uu}

      @{b}Vertical wheel acceleration@{ub}
        When you roll the mouse wheel it will give events of +1 or -1.
        With this setting it is possible to multiply these values by
        anything between -100 to +100 which makes things scroll faster
        if it is programmed correctly.

        A negative acceleration value will make the wheel inverted.

      @{b}Horizontal wheel acceleration@{ub}
        Some mice (or mouses as plural of computer mouse can be called)
        have a second scroll wheel. This is often used for horizontal
        scrolling.

        A negative acceleration value will make the wheel inverted.

      @{b}Also send the old NewMouse event@{ub}
        When this is enabled, Macc will also send NewMouse events when
        receiveing an normal OS4 mouse wheel event. This will make old,
        non-OS4 program to work as well.

        A little note on why OS4 didn't use NewMouse as mouse wheel event
        (my own version): This is because NewMouse uses the few remaining
        rawkey codes. This is bad because the wheel is no key. It is also
        bad because we run out of rawkey codes and thus cannot expand in
        the future.
          OS4 therefore defines a new class for this where it uses the
        coordinate variables of the input-event to set the wheel movement.
        This has the advantage of being multiplicable, i.e. scroll up is
        not a code of its own, but a mouse wheel event with a negative Y
        value.
          To accelerate a NewMouse wheel event one simply need to send
        more events which is inefficient.

      @{b}Vertical NewMouse wheel acceleration@{ub}
        Sets how many NewMouse events should be sent for every vertical
        wheel tick. Due to the primitive implementation of NewMouse there
        cannot be negative values and it would be impractical to send more
        than a few events at a time. This value is therefore limited to
        between 1 and 10.

      @{b}Horizontal NewMouse wheel acceleration@{ub}
        Sets how many NewMouse events should be sent for every horizontal
        wheel tick. Due to the primitive implementation of NewMouse there
        cannot be negative values and it would be impractical to send more
        than a few events at a time. This value is therefore limited to
        between 1 and 10.


   @{u}Settings@{uu}

      @{b}Input-handler priority@{ub}
        This is a priority setting for the input handler. If you experience
        problems with some other macc or something you can try and change
        the priority by changing this value.

        It is not a task priority. The Console has pri 0, Intution has pri 50.
        If you intend to get something out of this it is adviced to give
        a higher priority than Intuition. Default is pri 70. Highest pri
        is 127 and lowest is -128.

        This value will not change in realtime. You need to restart Macc
        before a change will take effect.


@endnode

@node news "News.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}News and Changes
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} It is now possible to accelerate the mousewheel(s).

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Now Macc can translate mouse-wheel events into NewMouse wheel
           events while still accelerating and sending the original OS4
           event. This will make the wheel work in programs like KingCON,
           CubicIDE, DOpus4, AmIRC, AmigaAmp(volume), etc.

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added the input-handler priority to the GUI.


 @{b}v1.0
 ~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} First release.


@endnode

